<div class="entry">
<h1>High Profile Email Accounts That Have Been Hacked</h1>
<i>Jan 06, 2011 by Damien Ramé</i><br>&nbsp;<br>

<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td style="vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;">
	<!-- Digg -->
	<script type="text/javascript">
	(function() {
	var s = document.createElement('SCRIPT'), s1 = document.getElementsByTagName('SCRIPT')[0];
	s.type = 'text/javascript';
	s.async = true;
	s.src = 'http://widgets.digg.com/buttons.js';
	s1.parentNode.insertBefore(s, s1);
	})();
	</script>
	<a class="DiggThisButton DiggCompact"></a>
	
</td><td style="vertical-align:middle;">
	<!-- Twitter -->
	<a href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-count="horizontal" data-via="Vircom_Inc" data-related="EmailSecMatters">Tweet</a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js"></script>

</td><td style="vertical-align:middle;">
	<!-- Reddit -->
	<a href="http://reddit.com/submit" onclick="window.location = 'http://reddit.com/submit?url=' + encodeURIComponent(window.location); return false"> <img src="http://reddit.com/static/spreddit7.gif" alt="submit to reddit" border="0" /> </a>
	
</td></tr>
<table cellpadding=10 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr>
<td style="vertical-align:middle;">
	<!-- Delicious -->
	<script type="text/javascript" src="http://delicious-button.googlecode.com/files/jquery.delicious-button-1.0.min.js"></script>
	<a class="delicious-button-2" href="http://delicious.com/save">Save on Delicious</a>
	<script type="text/javascript">
	$(document).ready(function(){
	   $('a.delicious-button-2').deliciousButton({
		  url:'http://www.vircom.com/en/lp/high-profile-email-accounts-that-have-been-hacked'
		  ,title:'High Profile Email Accounts That Have Been Hacked'
		  ,button:'wide'
	   });
	});
	</script>

</td><td style="vertical-align:middle;">

	<!-- Facebook -->
	<iframe src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http://www.vircom.com/en/lp/high-profile-email-accounts-that-have-been-hacked&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=250&amp;action=like&amp;colorscheme=light&amp;height=21" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width:250px; height:21px;" allowTransparency="true"></iframe>


</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</table>

&nbsp;<br>

<p>Obtaining private information like someone’s email password is frighteningly easy to do on the web. We often think the hackers behind such computer attacks are using highly sophisticated methods to gather sensitive information. However, in many cases it can be as easy as finding out your birthday or the high school you went to. You may be surprised to find out how many high profile email accounts have been compromised in exactly this way. Protecting your password is protecting your identity. The following article will outline some celebrities and other high profile figures whose email accounts have been compromised, often because of their own negligence or unawareness about the potential threats which exist online. These stories show that on the World Wide Web, anyone can be a target and your best guard against hacking and other online threats is to create strong passwords and take your online privacy seriously. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Sarah Palin</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/sarah_palin.jpg" width=200 height=200 border=0 title="Sarah Palin">
</td><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/david_kernell.jpg" width=148 height=200 border=0 title="David Kernell">
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> September 16, 2008</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> Hacker David Kernell (son of longtime Democratic state representative Mike Kernell of Memphis), obtained access to Governor Palin’s email account using Yahoo!&#8216;s account recovery for forgotten passwords. Simply by looking up biographical details from Wikipedia such as her high school and birth date- the then 20-year-old took a whole “15 seconds” to snatch her password.&nbsp; Kernell then posted several pages of Palin&#8217;s email on 4chan&#8217;s /b/ board.</p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Kernell was found guilty on two counts: the felony of anticipatory obstruction of justice and the misdemeanor of unauthorized access to a computer. He was sentenced on November 12, 2010, to 1 year plus a day in federal custody (served in a halfway house) followed by three years of supervised release. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Salma Hayek</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/salma_hayek.jpg" width=150 height=200 border=0 title="Salma Hayek">
</td><td>
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> April 23, 2009</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> Like the Sarah Palin hack, 4chan was able to invade Hayek’s MobileMe account by finding out her date of birth and guessing her security word, which was apparently the name of her most successful movie role (clearly <strong>Cesca Giggles</strong> from <em>Spy Kids 3D: Game Over</em>)</p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Far from unearthing anything scandalous, the breach of security only revealed how ordinary the star’s life really is. She downloads iPhone apps. She gets designer clothes delivered to her apartment and she likes to schedule Japanese face massage appointments. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Paris Hilton</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/paris-hilton.jpg" width=153 height=200 border=0 title="Paris Hilton">
</td><td>
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> February 20, 2005</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> A year earlier, hacker Nicholas Jacobsen had obtained illegal access to the backend of the T-Mobile USA network and netted information on 400 of the company&#8217;s customers. Hilton was one of a number of celebrity cell phones that was reportedly compromised. </p>
<p>In February of 2005, hackers from the “illmob” website (a Hacker Organization) posted dirty camphone shots from Paris’ phone, her notebook, and her address book, which included names like: Christina Aguilera, Fred Durst, Jermaine Dupri, Stephen King, Lindsay Lohan, Ashlee Simpson, Twiggy, Usher, and Vin Diesel. (Stephen King, <em>really?</em>)</p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Every celebrity in Paris’ address book had to change their phone numbers.</p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Rapper &#8220;The Game&#8221;</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/the_game.jpg" width=253 height=200 border=0 title="Rapper 'The Game'">
</td><td>
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> March 15, 2010</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> <a href="http://www.mediatakeout.com/2010/39506-uh_oh_somebody_hacks_into_rapper_the_games_email____releases_his_financial_statement____check_out_how_dude_spends_his_money_52000_a_month.html">MediaTakeOut.com</a> was the first to receive word that the email account of West Coast rapper The Game had been hacked and that some of his personal financial information had been leaked. The financial statement listed all his monthly expenses (totaling 52k), included 4 mortgages (3 for his homes totaling $13,500, and 1 for his mother’s home for $3,250). He also listed his child support obligations - with one baby’s mother (Tiffney) getting $8,000 a month and the other (Aleska) getting $1,800. </p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong>&nbsp; The perpetrator(s) of the email hack are still at large and most probably will remain so. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Chinese human rights activists</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/google_china.jpg" width=300 height=200 border=0 title="Chinese human rights activists'">
</td><td>
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> January 2010 (Some of the accounts of well-known human rights advocates in China may have been compromised as early as 2007.)</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> The Gmail accounts of dozens of human rights advocates in China as well as the US and Europe had been routinely accessed by third parties. Google supposed the computers became infected when users clicked on links in their emails or malicious documents attached to them. Contacts told American diplomats that the hacking attacks against Google were ordered by China&#8217;s top ruling body.</p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Google leaves China. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Janet Robinson, Michael Bloomberg, Diane Sawyer and 114, 000 other iPad users</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0>
<tr><td><img src="/images/email-security-articles/high-profile-emails-hacked/i_hack.jpg" width=268 height=200 border=0 title="iPad iHACK'">
</td><td>
</td></tr>
</table><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p><strong>When:</strong> June 2010</p>

<p><strong>How:</strong> Hackers from “Goatse Security” exploited a vulnerability on the AT&amp;T website and obtained the email addresses of over 114,000 Apple iPad owners. Goatse Security said it obtained its data through a script on AT&amp;T&#8217;s website, accessible to anyone on the Internet. The information exposed included subscribers&#8217; email addresses, as well as an associated ID used to authenticate the subscriber on AT&amp;T&#8217;s network. </p>

<p><strong>Aftermath:</strong> Goatse Security notified AT&amp;T of the breach. AT&amp;T laid blame on the security group. The security hole was closed. Apple remained silent on the breached privacy. AT&amp;T apologized for the mishap.&nbsp; </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br>
</p><h2 class="bodyheader">Protecting against email threats</h2><p>
&nbsp;<br></p>

<p>Email threats can take on many forms, from spam, phishing scams to viruses guised as attachments from trusted sources like your bank or even a friend. An email from a friend&#8217;s ID is just as likely to contain a virus or malware as a stranger&#8217;s. The best thing to do is always contact the source directly to find out if they really sent you something. Also, NEVER EVER give out sensitive information like your credit card number or your social insurance number. If it is being requested, again, call the company to find out why. Maintaining updated email scanning and Anti-virus software is one of the best defenses against unwanted threats so use it to scan all your incoming emails. Lastly, a strong password should have a minimum of eight characters (more is always better) and use both upper and lowercase letters. The strength of a password is strongly determined by how frequently password guesses can be tested by an attacker and how securely information on user passwords is stored and transmitted.</p>



